The Longford / Coleshill table. Supplied by Goodison, if not to a direct design by Kent than v much under his influence. Goodison executed his (IMO) greatest commission for Longford- where much still remains, though this beauty was eventually removed to Coleshill, that stunning house in the manner of Inigo Jones, whose destruction in the latter half of the 20th c will always be amongst England’s greatest architectural losses. Now on permanent display at the V&A for everyone’s enjoyment.

“He grows his hair rather long, because that is how he likes it. Sometimes he grows a beard. Even in his relatively beardless periods he looks like a debonair model for Romney or Raeburn who, having been to a successful party on the night before, has slight circles under his eyes and hasn’t had the time to shave for the sitting. He is coolly assured, easy to talk to, pleased if anyone is interested in his possessions, about which he is informative without being boring. His fortunate disposition, one fancies, is accurately reflected on his face.” So wrote Valentine Lawford of Peregrine Eliot, captured here by Horst. Vogue, 1966

The Picture Gallery at Longford: without question one of the greatest English interiors. Still hung in the original green damask installed in 1740 (at the then astounding cost of £170), it contains one of the best private collections of pictures in the country and arguably the best commission of furniture that Goodison ever executed.

At a bit of a loss for words on this one, but over the past 18 months it’s been an incredible experience to get to work with Castle Howard and Watts on reproducing a range of textile documents and wallpapers from the vast CH archive, which are now available to order through @watts1874. We spent countless hours on trying to replicate the feeling of the original documents, and after dozens of trials, they look fantastic. This collection is the end product of so much effort from everyone at Watts, the curators at CH, and especially the Howards themselves — it’s been a true honor to get work on it. And a big thank you to @houseandgardenuk @hattabyng and @montgomeryphoto for capturing it.

One of the several soaring polonaise beds at CH proved to be the perfect foil for the ‘Howard’ indienne, that we reproduced with @watts1874 based off of a document in the archives — I’m so proud of the transformation of this room. A decorator’s work is the product of the efforts of many, and it’s been incredible to work with the best of Britain. The bed was beautifully recovered and rehung by @rdrobinsupholsterersltd; it took a team of four to reassemble it, working until nearly midnight to get it right. @rushmatters spent nearly a week on-site laying the acres of rush matting I had wanted and the brilliant wall color and picture hang were the magic of @aleccobbe and @alexeymoskvin, perfectly executed by @nick_hespandjones.
Mosquito Island in winter by Peter Ralston

I don’t work for accolades, but to say this is a great honor would be an understatement. If I had any idea seven years ago what building a business would entail, I doubt I’d have done it — I still find it a challenge everyday but I’m so proud of the work that myself and my small team are creating. At the core of my work are my incredible clients, and it’s to them that I give my most profound gratitude — for allowing me to do what I love daily and for trusting in my taste and abilities. I’m immeasurably grateful to @houseandgardenuk and @hattabyng for their enormous support since the beginning. ❤️

As I prepare to spend the next two weeks in Maine working on a special project, I’m reminded of my introduction to this v important place: Mosquito Island, a remote and inaccessible island populated by sheep that my family rented for the first few summers I was alive. With just one house, a mid-18th c beauty that withstood centuries of inclement weather (pictured here), it was an unspoiled pastoral paradise and surely where, in the absence of any form of modern technology or communication, my vivid imagination was fostered. Wisely, through regrettably, we resisted the urge to purchase the island when it came up for sale after a few years — and now the house, while still standing, bears little resemblance to the earnest, quiet edifice that we called home

To say I’m excited to share this story is a gross understatement. As many know, for almost three years I’m been slowly, and cautiously, working on redecorating areas of Castle Howard, a house which needs no introduction. Needless to say, it’s the job of a lifetime — and likely will (and should) take more than a lifetime. The great joy of it aside, it’s also been a tremendous learning experience, and in addition to having the greatest possible partners in Nick and Vicky Howard, I’ve been astounded by the extraordinary talent of every person involved from the curators to the curtain makers. This summer over the course of a week, my dear friend @moorederry came up to document what has been done so far — full circle of a sort, as he had photographed much of the house for Nick’s father, the late Lord Howard, in 1977. I’m forever grateful to @cabanamagazine and @martinamondadori for showcasing the work of myself and many, so beautifully in this latest issue. And to @cultofg and @jamiesharp for the many hours that went into making these rooms come to life on the page.
The Gold Library. The tufted sofa was a sleeping Victorian beauty pulled from the attics, which spent six months being restored and recovered in a faded damask from @watts1874.
Best way to spend my birthday

Inspired by an existing worn paper in a dressing room, I chose this paper by Mauny, which is a perfect foil to the gilt-framed views of Naples. The Victorian brass bed didn’t already exist in the house, but it surely could have.

At home in front of Min Hogg’s wonderful bookcase, on generous long-term loan to me from @alexandermollyc and above it a parcel gilt frieze designed by Wyatt for Devonshire House from @jamesgrahamstewart
While everything in this bedroom, including the bed and chimneypiece, were newly created or purchased — my hope is that they look as though they’ve been here for ages.

The CH dining room, with its hand-mixed terracotta colored walls, and wonderfully gilded woodwork — all expertly done last summer by @nick_hespandjones. The Great Houses and Gardens of England exhibition was an attempt to show how these houses and gardens are lived in now; the incredible work that goes in to keeping them alive for generations to come and for the public to enjoy. It therefore made perfect sense to paint decorator @remy_renzullo; documenting his work at @castle_howard
